### MPLS On-Path Telemetry Network Action Flag for OAM
Presented by Haoyu Song ([MPLS On-Path Telemetry Network Action Flag for OAM](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mpls-mpls-on-path-telemetry-network-action-flag-for-oam-00))
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-mpls-on-path-telemetry-flag](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-mpls-on-path-telemetry-flag/)

*   **Technical Details:** The draft proposes using a single flag (the "P-bit" at recommended bit position 42) to trigger postcard-mode telemetry data collection. This decouples the trigger from the detailed data configuration (which is managed out-of-band via control/management planes). Proposing bit 42 avoids the first 24 bits to remain ECMP-safe and complies with RFC 9994.
*   **Discussion:**
    *   **Greg Mirsky** asked how this differs from IOAM Direct Export (DEX). **Haoyu Song** clarified that DEX requires user packets to carry specific telemetry instructions in the header, whereas this solution only uses a single flag and relies on the control/management plane to specify the data to collect.
    *   **Greg Mirsky** expressed concern that the proposed approach has too little control over what data is collected and compared it to Alternate Marking. **Haoyu Song** replied that these methods are complementary and serve different use cases. Greg noted his view that the functionality already exists via other methods.

