### Signaling RSVP-TE Tunnels on an SR-MPLS Forwarding Plane Using Adjacency Segment Identifiers
Presented by Pawan Beeram ([Signaling RSVP-TE Tunnels on an SR-MPLS Forwarding Plane Using Adjacency Segment Identifiers](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mpls-08-signaling-rsvp-te-tunnels-on-an-sr-mpls-forwarding-plane-using-adjacency-segment-identifiers-01))

*   **Technical Details:** Builds upon RFC 8577. It proposes using Segment Routing (SR) adjacency sets to realize a shared MPLS forwarding plane over which RSVP-TE tunnels are established. This eliminates the duplicate label systems required when running both SR and RSVP-TE T-link labels. It preserves distributed RSVP-TE features (admission control, auto-bandwidth, preemption) on top of an SR forwarding plane.
*   **Discussion:**
    *   **Sasha Vainshtein** asked about using protected adjacency SIDs and its impact on facility Fast Reroute (FRR). **Pawan Beeram** answered that RFC 8577 procedures apply, utilizing a separate protection SID at the Point of Local Repair (PLR) to run facility backup.
    *   **Zafar Ali** strongly objected to the draft, stating that introducing signaling state into a segment routing forwarding plane violates the stateless architecture of SR. Pawan responded that this addresses environments requiring distributed bandwidth engineering on a unified forwarding plane.
    *   **Himanshu Shah** raised a clarification question regarding how EXP bits are mapped and queued at each hop since labels are popped. Pawan stated it behaves like standard SR policies but agreed to add clarification text on EXP handling.

