### Signaling Optimization Objective and Bounded Metrics for MPLS Fast Reroute Backup LSP Tunnels
Presented by Pawan Beeram ([Signaling Optimization Objective and Bounded Metrics for MPLS Fast Reroute Backup LSP Tunnels](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mpls-09-signaling-optimization-objective-and-bounded-metrics-for-mpls-fast-reroute-backup-lsp-tunnels-02))

*   **Technical Details:** This proposal introduces the `Fast_FRR_Extension` object in RSVP Path messages, allowing the ingress node to specify path constraints—such as optimization objectives (e.g., TE metric or delay) and hard bounded metrics (e.g., maximum latency limits)—to guide the PLR's backup path calculation. It is backwards compatible; non-supporting PLRs fall back to local policy.
*   **Discussion:**
    *   **Adrian Farrel** inquired about the urgency of the requested early IANA code points. Pawan indicated that while they are shipping an implementation, adopting the draft first is fine as the registries are new.
    *   **Zafar Ali** expressed concern over "diminishing returns" and added complexity, arguing that local policies at the PLRs have successfully managed backup paths for over twenty years without needing head-end coordination. Pawan replied that modern traffic profiles are highly fluid, requiring more granular control. Zafar also questioned the necessity of early code points for interoperability if there are no other active implementations.

